@node not31 "OFFICIAL STATEMENT OF AROS TEAM STATUS"

OFFICIAL STATEMENT OF @{B}AROS @{UB}TEAM STATUS
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
This is an official statement about the current status of the @{B}AROS @{UB}project.

As of writing, the @{B}AROS @{UB}source code is about 29MB and about 56% of all functions
are implemented (13% more are currently in progress).

Currently, we are working hard on finishing graphics, layers and intuition based
on  our  new  @{B}HIDD @{UB} system.  The  @{B}HIDD @{UB} system  will allow us to put any kind of
hardware  below  @{B}AROS @{UB}with only very little effort for people who want/need/have
to  write a driver for a new piece of hardware. This work is mostly done by @{I}Nils
Henrik  Lorentzen @{UI} and @{I}Stefan Berger@{UI}. The main goal is to have a version of @{B}AROS@{UB}
which  can  open a screen, create windows on it and let the use manipulate them.
Currently,  @{B}X11 @{UB} is  used  to  create  the  windows  and  @{B}X11 @{UB}also allows one to
manipulate them. The time-frame for this is May.

@{I}Michael Schulz @{UI}has committed very promising code which can be compiled, saved on
a  floppy and then be used to boot a small part of @{B}AROS @{UB}on a bare @{B}IBM @{UB}compatible
@{B}PC@{UB}.  When  the  new graphics system is ready, writing a @{B}VGA @{UB}driver should take a
day (if not less) and @{B}AROS @{UB}should be able to open a workbench screen and windows
on  it.  No  workbench  yet, though :-) @{B}AROS @{UB}does already boot but it doesn't do
much yet.

The  next  step  would  be  to  finish the console.device (half of it is already
finished)  and  put  the  input.device  on  top  of the @{B}HIDD @{UB}system. This should
integrate  @{B}X11 @{UB} (or whatever is below @{B}AROS@{UB}) nicely into the @{B}AROS @{UB}system allowing
to  open  a  shell  on  an  @{B}AROS @{UB} screen.  This  will  be done by @{I}Nils @{UI}and @{I}Johan
Alfredsson@{UI},  who  is also working on the Commodities. This should take about one
month.

When  the @{B}HIDD@{UB}s for @{B}PC @{UB}hardware are finished (mostly done by @{I}Michael Schulz@{UI}), it
should  be  possible  to boot @{B}AROS @{UB}from a diskette and use a shell to enter some
commands.  An @{B}FFS @{UB}file system also seems at the brink of completion, so creating
an  @{B}Amiga @{UB} partition  and  installing  it  on  the  hard  disk will then soon be
possible. No time frame has been set for all this, yet. It mainly depends on how
much  (correct)  information  books  about @{B}PC @{UB}hardware contain, how the code for
@{B}Linux @{UB} looks  like and such. @{I}Branko Collin @{UI}is meanwhile working on improving the
documentation  (the  web  pages  are  not exactly... "sexy" :-), fixing the many
typos and writing documentation about how to write documentation.

@{I}Kars  de  Jong @{UI} is  working  on  the @{B}Linux@{UB}/@{B}m68k @{UB}port of @{B}AROS @{UB}which allows to run
binary  @{B}Amiga @{UB} software.  Some simple programs already work. When not working on
Layers,  @{I}Stefan Berger @{UI}tries to compile programs from Fish disks and @{B}AmiNET @{UB}work
on @{B}AROS@{UB}.

@{I}Bernhard Fastenrath @{UI}and @{I}Aaron Digulla @{UI}work on merging @{B}AROS @{UB}with @{B}UAE @{UB}which should
allow  to make @{B}UAE @{UB}faster and run native @{B}Amiga @{UB}programs in an emulator when @{B}AROS@{UB}
is  able  to  run  standalone  (that  is,  without  the  help of @{B}Linux@{UB}). We will
investigate  the  necessary  steps  and do tests during March. At the end of the
month, the next step will be decided.

@{I}Przemyslaw  Szczygielski @{UI} and  @{I}Claus  Herrmann @{UI} are  looking at @{B}PPC @{UB}support. The
former  for  a port to @{B}LinuxPPC @{UB}and the latter for making @{B}Exec @{UB}on the @{B}Amiga @{UB}work
on  @{B}PPC @{UB} (thus  using  the  power of the @{B}PPC @{UB}to run @{B}Amiga @{UB}software on an @{B}Amiga@{UB}).
@{I}Przemo @{UI}hopes for some results in May and I must convince @{I}Claus @{UI}to merge his code
with ours :-)

What  the  future  might  bring, who knows. The main goals right now are to make
@{B}AROS @{UB} work  as a standalone system which can boot from a hard disk, writing some
drivers  for the @{B}HIDD @{UB}system so we can see if everything really fits to where it
belongs,  rewrite  the most complex part of the @{B}AmigaOS@{UB}: Intuition, Graphics and
Layers.

The  future  will hopefully see a commercial version of @{B}AROS @{UB}(so that we can pay
@{B}Amiga  Inc. @{UB} some  money  so  they keep calm), a free version of @{B}AROS @{UB}(just like
@{B}Linux@{UB}: free without support or commercial with support), many more @{B}HIDD@{UB}s, a port
of @{B}AROS @{UB}to @{B}PPC@{UB}. But that doesn't mean that you can sit back, relax and watch our
progress  (which  is  now  updated daily on (@{B}www.aros.org/progress.gif@{UB}). We need
you!

Currently,  more  and  more  parts  of  @{B}AROS @{UB}are being finished and we need some
real-world code to test @{B}AROS@{UB}. What code would that be? Here are the criteria:
  * It must only use pure @{B}AmigaOS @{UB}calls (no @{B}MUI @{UB}or such)
  * No  hardware  banging  or  calls to things like "MrgCop()", "CWait()" or the
    like  (usually  functions  which  directly  relate  to  some  @{B}Amiga @{UB}hardware
    specific feature). Most Blitter-Functions are ok, however.
  * NO ASSEMBLER CODE!
  * It  should  compile  with  recent  versions of @{B}SAS/C@{UB}, @{B}GCC@{UB}, @{B}StormC @{UB}or another
    @{B}ANSI-C @{UB}compiler.
  * They should be not too big (don't send in 1.5MB of source code, yet).

If you happen to have such a gem, then send it to: @{I}aros-code@aros.fh-konstanz.de@{UI}

Please  make  absolutely  clear  if  you mind if your code is published with the
source code of @{B}AROS @{UB}or not. We promise that we won't touch any copyright notices
(except  for adding them if they are missing, so you get your credit). It's just
that  you might not want that the code is revealed for any reason which would be
ok for us. We just need to know :-)

@{I}Aaron Digulla @{UI}(on behalf of the @{B}AROS @{UB}Team)
