@node not47 "UPDATE ON THE CYBERSTORM G3/G4"

UPDATE ON THE @{B}CYBERSTORM G3@{UB}/@{B}G4@{UB}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Only  four days after the first announcement of the @{B}Cyberstorm G3@{UB}/@{B}G4 @{UB}project, we
have seen a very positive and exciting feedback by the @{B}Amiga @{UB}community, which we
highly  appreciate  and which supports our hope that we can realize this project
(although we still have to collect a large number of preorders).

At  the  same time, a lot of questions came up, and also a lot of comments about
the features of the board. We have taken those into consideration, and can today
already  announce  that  we  have  improved the specifications of the @{B}CYBERSTORM
G3@{UB}/@{B}G4 @{UB} Accelerator;  please read below about the new feature. We would also like
to  address  some questions which remained open or have been asked by many @{B}Amiga@{UB}
users, so please read on to hear the latest news about this stunning project.

        ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@{U}Specification Update: @{B}UW-SCSI @{UB}on board at no additional cost @{UU}

Reacting  on the large number of requests, we have decided to integrate an @{B}Ultra
Wide  SCSI II @{UB}controller (Fast-20 standard) on the @{B}Cyberstorm G3@{UB}/@{B}G4 @{UB}board, which
will perform @{B}SCSI @{UB}bus transfers in single-ended and differential mode with up to
40 MB/s (synchronous @{B}Ultra SCSI @{UB}(Fast-20) transfers). This @{B}SCSI @{UB}chip is based on
the  same  core (and comes from the same vendor) as the powerful @{B}SCSI @{UB}controller
which   is   already  standard  on  our  @{B}Cyberstorm  MkIII @{UB} and  @{B}Cyberstorm  PPC@{UB}
Accelerators.  And  yes,  it's  true:  This  powerful add-on will cost the @{B}Amiga@{UB}
users, who decide to buy the @{B}Cyberstorm G3@{UB}/@{B}G4 @{UB}board, not a single Cent more than
we have announced on @{I}March 19, 1999@{UI}.

        ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@{U}Dealer inquiries Welcome!@{UU}

Dealer  inquiries  for  the  @{B}Cyberstorm G3@{UB}/@{B}G4 @{UB}board are welcome. We are happy to
take pre-orders from dealers and distributors, as well as OEMs and VARs all over
the  world,  who  can  show their support for the @{B}Amiga @{UB}with such preorders, and
prepare  for  future  business.  Dealers  will  receive a common discount on the
regular  list price of the @{B}Cyberstorm G3@{UB}/@{B}G4 @{UB}board, when placing preorders at the
listed  preorder  conditions.  If  you  are  a  dealer/OEM/VAR and want to place
orders,  don't  hesitate:  simply enter your customer number, select "dealer" on
the order form, and enter the quantity of @{B}Cyberstorm G3@{UB}/@{B}G4 @{UB}boards you would like
to purchase in the comments field. We'll get back to you with the pricing we can
offer you, depending on the quantity.

        ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Now  here  are some answers to typical questions (or concerns) that we have seen
in the past days:

  * @{I}Why do you need so many preorders (which you may not get)?@{UI}

    The quantity of 1,000 perorders is important to justify the investments into
    this  new  product.  It  must  not  be  underestimated  how  much technology
    knowledge  is necessary to realize it on our side. But there is also another
    important  factor,  which  we  have considered: Once the project starts with
    1,000  secured  sales,  it provides the security of a minimum installed user
    base for developers. We doubt that developers would like to start optimizing
    software for a base of several hundred users only.

  * @{I}Why don't you offer cheaper versions with slower processors?@{UI}

    There are two major reasons for that:
      - Price/performance  relation:  As a large part of the cost of the product
        goes  into  the  board  logic and development cost, the use of a cheaper
        processor would not save so much. Right now, e.g. a 300MHz version would
        only  be DM 300 or 15% cheaper, but offer 25% less performance (and CPUs
        below  300MHz  are  not  longer  built  by  @{B}IBM @{UB} and  @{B}Motorola@{UB}, and will
        therefore probably not be available in the second half of the year).
      - Absolute  performance:  To  emulate @{B}68k @{UB}code at least at the performance
        level  of  appx. an @{B}68060 @{UB}(and maybe even offer improved performance for
        emulated  @{B}68k @{UB} software,  with  highly  optimized  emulators),  we  have
        evaluated  that  400MHz @{B}G3 @{UB}performance should be an entry level product.
        We  don't  want  to  offer a product which may be a drawback for current
        high-end users (please also see the next question/answer about emulation
        speed).

  * @{I}How fast will the @{B}Cyberstorm G3@{UB}/@{B}G4 @{UB}operate in @{B}68k @{UB}emulation?@{UI}

    This  can  currently  only  be  estimated,  based  on  reports  of emulation
    performance  on  @{B}604e @{UB} based boards, and by evaluating emulation performance
    for  other  CPUs  on  other  @{B}G3 @{UB} based systems. Based on currently available
    benchmarks, an optimized software emulation on a 400MHz @{B}G3 @{UB}with 1MB backside
    cache  and  100MHz  SDRAM  memory (as provided by the @{B}Cyberstorm G3@{UB}/@{B}G4@{UB}) e.g.
    compares  well  to  a  120MHz  @{B}Pentium @{UB}chip. This performance, together with
    preliminary  @{B}68k @{UB} emulator benchmarks, gives us good hope that even emulated
    @{B}68k @{UB} software  can run some 50-80% faster than a real @{B}68060@{UB}. Of course, lots
    of already existing @{B}PPC @{UB}applications will really fly on this board...

  * @{I}Why is the @{B}Cyberstorm G3@{UB}/@{B}G4 @{UB}board so expensive?@{UI}

    A question we can't understand - as the @{B}Cyberstorm G3@{UB}/@{B}G4 @{UB}is offered for very
    a  reasonable  price. A ZIF CPU module for the @{B}PowerMac @{UB}currently costs some
    DM  1,700  in  Germany  or US$ 800 and up in the US - and this is only a CPU
    module,  without  memory  subsystem,  @{B}PCI @{UB} bridge  and  interface,  or  @{B}SCSI@{UB}
    controller.  And  there  is  definitely  no  other  solution  for  the @{B}Amiga@{UB}
    available,  or announced right now, that would offer the same performance at
    a comparable or even lower price.

    Another  cost-reducing advantage, especially compared to other solutions, is
    that  the  user  who  purchases a @{B}Cyberstorm G3@{UB}/@{B}G4 @{UB}can sell the existing CPU
    card  on  the second-hand market, as the @{B}Cyberstorm G3@{UB}/@{B}G4 @{UB}fully replaces the
    current  CPU.  By selling e.g. an existing @{B}68060 @{UB}processor card, the cost of
    upgrading  to the @{B}Cyberstorm G3@{UB}/@{B}G4 @{UB}can be reduced significantly. This is not
    possible  with  solutions e.g. for the @{B}Zorro @{UB}slot, which require the @{B}68k @{UB}CPU
    and don't allow the user to sell it.

  * @{I}Can I use my @{B}CyberVisionPPC @{UB}on the @{B}Cyberstorm G3@{UB}/@{B}G4@{UB}?@{UI}

    Likely  not.  If  someone  uses  a @{B}CyberVisionPPC@{UB}, he also owns a @{B}Cyberstorm
    MkIII @{UB} or  @{B}PPC@{UB}.  We  recommend  in  such  a  case to sell the @{B}CyberVisionPPC@{UB}
    together with the @{B}Cyberstorm Mk III @{UB}or @{B}PPC@{UB}, when upgrading to the @{B}Cyberstorm
    G3@{UB}/@{B}G4@{UB}.  With  the  prices of new 3D @{B}PCI @{UB}gfx cards as low as never before, we
    recommend  to go for a new generation gfx card then. We also encourage other
    developers (and will happily support them) to bring new technologies such as
    @{B}3Dfx Banshee@{UB}, @{B}ATI Rage 128@{UB}, or others to the @{B}Amiga@{UB}.

  * @{I}Why don't you built an @{B}1200 @{UB}board?@{UI}

    There  are  too  many  technical  restrictions on such a product, because of
    which  a  development does not make sense. It must also be noted that such a
    product  would  require  a  tower case with a stronger power supply at least
    (there  is  no  chance  to  design  it  to fit into @{B}A1200 @{UB}desktops). We will
    discuss  with manufacturers of tower cases, if e.g. a simple and inexpensive
    interface  between  the @{B}A1200 @{UB}slot and the @{B}A4000 @{UB}compatible CPU connector on
    the  @{B}Cyberstorm  G3@{UB}/@{B}G4 @{UB} can  be  realized (as already available as a part of
    @{B}Zorro-III @{UB} expansion  boards).  With  such  a solution, the @{B}Cyberstorm G3@{UB}/@{B}G4@{UB}
    could be used in @{B}A1200 @{UB}tower systems without significant additional costs.

  * @{I}Why don't you build a complete new system?@{UI}

    There  are  several  issues  which would need to be resolved before we could
    decide  to  built such a system. Just to mention two major factors, we would
    need
      - full support for such a project by @{B}Amiga, Inc.@{UB}
      - a  demand  strong  enough  to  sell  3,000-5,000  units of a stand-alone
        system.
    It  might  be  a  project  for  the  future,  but  yet  we  can't say if the
    circumstances will allow us to go for such a development.

        ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

That's  it  for today. If these informations and the specification update answer
your  questions,  and  have  convinced  you  to participate in this exciting new
development project, then go ahead and @{B}PLACE YOUR CYBERSTORM G3/G4 PREORDER NOW!@{UB}
